00:00:21.640 --> 00:00:25.060
PROFESSOR: All right, why don't
we go ahead and get started.

00:00:25.060 --> 00:00:27.680
So today what we
want to do is start

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:30.350
thinking a bit about evolution
in finite populations.

00:00:30.350 --> 00:00:32.549
And of course, what
we mean by that,

00:00:32.549 --> 00:00:36.530
is evolution in populations
where we have to really think

00:00:36.530 --> 00:00:38.750
about stochastic dynamics.

00:00:38.750 --> 00:00:42.120
And now in general,
just like in the context

00:00:42.120 --> 00:00:45.230
of gene networks within
cells, the situation

00:00:45.230 --> 00:00:47.250
where we have to worry
about stochastic dynamics

00:00:47.250 --> 00:00:50.570
is in the small
number kind of limit.

00:00:50.570 --> 00:00:53.690
What's perhaps surprising
about evolution

00:00:53.690 --> 00:00:56.720
is that they're always--
the small numbers

00:00:56.720 --> 00:00:58.570
are always important.

00:00:58.570 --> 00:01:00.570
Even if you're in
a large population,

00:01:00.570 --> 00:01:04.311
I'd say 10 to the 9 individuals,
if you want to study evolution,

00:01:04.311 --> 00:01:06.560
then you're interested in
cases where new mutants will

00:01:06.560 --> 00:01:07.560
arise in the population.

00:01:07.560 --> 00:01:10.270
And kind of by definition,
those new mutants

00:01:10.270 --> 00:01:14.040
start out as kind of a single
member of the population.

00:01:14.040 --> 00:01:16.450
Which means that in the
context of evolution,

00:01:16.450 --> 00:01:22.490
we always have to think about
stochastic type dynamics.

00:01:22.490 --> 00:01:25.500
Now the basic model that we're
going to use in this class

00:01:25.500 --> 00:01:30.440
is the Moran process,
which is a model that

00:01:30.440 --> 00:01:32.220
fixes population size.

00:01:32.220 --> 00:01:36.870
And then instead of having
discrete generations, where

00:01:36.870 --> 00:01:38.414
all the individuals
are reproducing

00:01:38.414 --> 00:01:40.580
at the same time-- which
is what you might have seen

00:01:40.580 --> 00:01:42.314
in the Wright-Fisher
process-- instead,

00:01:42.314 --> 00:01:43.980
we're going to think
about the situation

00:01:43.980 --> 00:01:47.180
where it occurs more stepwise.

00:01:47.180 --> 00:01:51.390
In the sense that individuals
reproduce one at a time.

00:01:51.390 --> 00:01:55.050
And then we contract the
dynamics of the population.

00:01:55.050 --> 00:01:57.900
So we're going to think about
both the situation where we're

00:01:57.900 --> 00:02:01.100
trying to understand neutral
dynamics, when we're tracking

00:02:01.100 --> 00:02:05.850
the composition of a population
when the fitness of individuals

00:02:05.850 --> 00:02:08.639
is equal or nearly equal.

00:02:08.639 --> 00:02:10.199
But because in
stochastic dynamics,

00:02:10.199 --> 00:02:12.250
there are interesting
things that happen.

00:02:12.250 --> 00:02:13.750
But then we'll get
into the question

00:02:13.750 --> 00:02:15.114
of non-neutral evolution.

00:02:15.114 --> 00:02:17.280
And really, we want to
consider both halves of that.

00:02:17.280 --> 00:02:20.020
All right, so in many cases,
in the context of evolution,

00:02:20.020 --> 00:02:24.520
we're interested in, or
focused on beneficial mutants.

00:02:24.520 --> 00:02:25.939
Now for those
beneficial mutants,

00:02:25.939 --> 00:02:27.730
one of the basic things
we're going to find

00:02:27.730 --> 00:02:33.460
is that even beneficial mutants
will typically go extinct.

00:02:33.460 --> 00:02:36.790
It doesn't mean that they're
not important over the long run.

00:02:36.790 --> 00:02:39.690
But it does mean that
there is a very real sense

00:02:39.690 --> 00:02:42.630
that randomness is
dominating the life of even

00:02:42.630 --> 00:02:44.360
beneficial mutants.

00:02:44.360 --> 00:02:46.140
And then finally,
if there's time,

00:02:46.140 --> 00:02:49.310
we will discuss this idea
of Muller's ratchet, which

00:02:49.310 --> 00:02:51.770
is basically pointing
out that if there

00:02:51.770 --> 00:02:55.190
are deleterious mutants or
mutations in the population,

00:02:55.190 --> 00:02:58.300
those deleterious
mutations can in some cases

00:02:58.300 --> 00:02:59.830
spread and fix in
the population.

00:02:59.830 --> 00:03:02.550
And when that
happens, you can have

00:03:02.550 --> 00:03:05.590
a decrease in the fitness
of a population over time.

00:03:05.590 --> 00:03:09.020
And this is particularly
a strong effect

00:03:09.020 --> 00:03:12.410
for small populations,
because small populations,

00:03:12.410 --> 00:03:15.290
they're not as effective,
what you might call filters,

00:03:15.290 --> 00:03:16.460
for selection.

00:03:19.054 --> 00:03:20.470
And so what we
want to do is start

00:03:20.470 --> 00:03:22.011
by thinking about
this Moran process.

00:03:27.887 --> 00:03:29.470
And the key feature
here is that we're

00:03:29.470 --> 00:03:34.840
going to have a constant
population size, constant N.

00:03:34.840 --> 00:03:37.060
And that's not
because we believe

00:03:37.060 --> 00:03:40.550
that real populations always
have a fixed population size,

00:03:40.550 --> 00:03:44.100
but rather, we want to
try to get some intuition

00:03:44.100 --> 00:03:45.570
in this simple model.

00:03:45.570 --> 00:03:47.950
And then of course, it's
reasonable to ask, well,

00:03:47.950 --> 00:03:51.410
which aspects of the
mathematics or intuition

00:03:51.410 --> 00:03:54.700
we develop are going to
change as a result of allowing

00:03:54.700 --> 00:03:56.974
fluctuations in the
total population size?

00:03:56.974 --> 00:03:58.390
But I think there's
a lot of value

00:03:58.390 --> 00:04:02.384
in starting out by analyzing
the simplest model that you can.

00:04:02.384 --> 00:04:03.800
So what we're going
to think about

00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:06.380
is a situation where we
have a population composed

00:04:06.380 --> 00:04:07.380
of N individuals.

00:04:07.380 --> 00:04:10.930
And for now we'll just
consider two types, A and B.

00:04:10.930 --> 00:04:16.890
And this is going to be a
model for asexually reproducing

00:04:16.890 --> 00:04:17.589
populations.

00:04:17.589 --> 00:04:19.440
Constant N, asexual.

00:04:22.964 --> 00:04:24.380
What that means
is, in particular,

00:04:24.380 --> 00:04:29.710
that we're going to assume
that an A individual can

00:04:29.710 --> 00:04:31.170
lead to two individuals.

00:04:31.170 --> 00:04:36.130
Similarity, a B individual
can lead to two B individuals.

00:04:36.130 --> 00:04:39.300
Right, so you can think about
this as, for example, a model

00:04:39.300 --> 00:04:43.450
for how microbial
populations may evolve.

00:04:43.450 --> 00:04:47.179
And for now, we will not
consider any mutations.

00:04:47.179 --> 00:04:49.470
All right, so we're going to
think about the process of

00:04:49.470 --> 00:04:51.400
assume that those mutations
are already there.

00:04:51.400 --> 00:04:54.510
So A and B could be different.

00:04:54.510 --> 00:04:56.630
They could have, for
example, different--

00:04:56.630 --> 00:04:59.270
they could be different
at some point mutation

00:04:59.270 --> 00:05:02.940
side of some gene that
is relevant for growing

00:05:02.940 --> 00:05:04.760
a low glucose
concentration, for example.

00:05:04.760 --> 00:05:06.170
OK?

00:05:06.170 --> 00:05:09.460
So here we're going to--
so this is birth slash

00:05:09.460 --> 00:05:11.860
division, and in particular
here we're going to, for now,

00:05:11.860 --> 00:05:14.420
assume no mutation.

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:17.200
So we'll assume that
A's always give birth

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:19.340
to A's, and B's always
give birth to B's.

00:05:29.550 --> 00:05:33.330
We'll follow the
nomenclature from the reading

00:05:33.330 --> 00:05:37.060
that you guys did last night,
Martin Nowak's book, chapter

00:05:37.060 --> 00:05:40.230
six, where we're going
to think about-- we're

00:05:40.230 --> 00:05:47.580
going to assume that there
are initially i A individuals,

00:05:47.580 --> 00:05:50.610
and therefore, N
minus i B individuals.

00:05:55.280 --> 00:06:02.840
Now we'll assume that the basic
process for the-- in this Moran

00:06:02.840 --> 00:06:06.630
process is that you have
reproduction, or birth, that's

00:06:06.630 --> 00:06:08.695
proportional to fitness.

00:06:15.942 --> 00:06:17.400
And then the
resulting kind of what

00:06:17.400 --> 00:06:20.170
you might call a daughter
cell replaces one member

00:06:20.170 --> 00:06:21.670
of the population at random.

00:06:21.670 --> 00:06:24.650
So there's birth and
then replacement.

00:06:24.650 --> 00:06:27.360
And indeed we'll assume
that replacement,

00:06:27.360 --> 00:06:28.860
that the daughter
cell, for example,

00:06:28.860 --> 00:06:34.040
could even replace the
mother cell, if we want.

00:06:34.040 --> 00:06:35.520
So this is just the birth.

00:06:35.520 --> 00:06:37.645
So A is going to lead--
there's going to be two As,

00:06:37.645 --> 00:06:39.290
and this new A will
have to replace

00:06:39.290 --> 00:06:41.570
one of the other individuals
in the population,

00:06:41.570 --> 00:06:43.210
to keep constant
population size.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:47.846
All right.

00:06:47.846 --> 00:06:50.230
Are there any questions
about the basic model?

00:06:52.960 --> 00:06:55.210
OK.

00:06:55.210 --> 00:06:58.945
So that, in principle,
here we can use this model

00:06:58.945 --> 00:07:01.600
to try to understand both
neutral and non-neutral

00:07:01.600 --> 00:07:02.100
evolution.

00:07:02.100 --> 00:07:04.391
But let's start out by thinking
about the neutral case.

00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:13.630
So in particular, the
fitness, rA is equal to rB.

00:07:16.330 --> 00:07:19.600
Now what I want to do
is, given the rules we

00:07:19.600 --> 00:07:24.730
just kind of laid out for you,
let's assume that i over n

00:07:24.730 --> 00:07:28.790
is equal to one third.

00:07:28.790 --> 00:07:32.870
So for now, we'll say, OK a
third of the population is A,

00:07:32.870 --> 00:07:35.610
2/3 is then B.

00:07:35.610 --> 00:07:38.640
And we can think about
these probabilities

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:41.230
of going from i to i
plus 1, as compared

00:07:41.230 --> 00:07:44.210
to going from i to i minus 1.

00:07:44.210 --> 00:07:48.280
So these are the probabilities
that in one cycle of birth

00:07:48.280 --> 00:07:52.600
replacement, the number of A's
goes up one or goes down one.

00:07:52.600 --> 00:07:56.420
Can you ever go up two or three
or four in the Moran process

00:07:56.420 --> 00:07:57.500
in one step?

00:07:57.500 --> 00:07:58.300
No.

00:07:58.300 --> 00:08:02.860
Because each step is always
one birth and one replacement.

00:08:02.860 --> 00:08:04.240
So you can move, at most, one.

00:08:04.240 --> 00:08:08.100
Do you always move--
does i change always?

00:08:08.100 --> 00:08:09.489
No.

00:08:09.489 --> 00:08:11.280
And what we want to
know is the probability

00:08:11.280 --> 00:08:16.620
of going from i to i plus 1,
as compared to the probability

00:08:16.620 --> 00:08:18.680
of going from i to i minus one.

00:08:18.680 --> 00:08:21.940
The ratio of these
probabilities is equal to what?

00:08:39.780 --> 00:08:42.380
We're considering a case
where the A's and B's have

00:08:42.380 --> 00:08:44.560
the same fitness,
so they're somehow

00:08:44.560 --> 00:08:48.190
equal per capita probability
of being chosen to reproduce.

00:08:48.190 --> 00:08:51.297
But there's-- but we're not
in a symmetric population

00:08:51.297 --> 00:08:52.130
distribution, right?

00:08:52.130 --> 00:08:57.300
So 1/3 of the population
is A, 2/3 is B.

00:08:57.300 --> 00:09:00.800
So I'll give you 20 seconds
to think about this.

00:09:26.130 --> 00:09:27.570
All right, do you
need more time?

00:09:31.450 --> 00:09:32.670
Everybody nod or shake.

00:09:32.670 --> 00:09:35.490
Do you need more time?

00:09:35.490 --> 00:09:35.990
OK.

00:09:35.990 --> 00:09:37.990
I'll give you another 10
seconds, because it's--

00:09:49.120 --> 00:09:51.350
Let's go ahead and
see where we are.

00:09:51.350 --> 00:09:52.530
Ready?

00:09:52.530 --> 00:09:55.850
Three, two, one.

00:09:55.850 --> 00:09:56.510
All right.

00:09:56.510 --> 00:10:01.780
We have a wide range of
different answers here.

00:10:01.780 --> 00:10:03.020
OK, perfect.

00:10:03.020 --> 00:10:06.599
This is exactly the
situation that we hope for.

00:10:06.599 --> 00:10:07.640
So turn to your neighbor.

00:10:07.640 --> 00:10:09.420
You should certainly be
able to find somebody

00:10:09.420 --> 00:10:10.480
that disagrees with you.

00:10:10.480 --> 00:10:12.990
So if the first person you
turn to agrees with you,

00:10:12.990 --> 00:10:14.699
try to find somebody
else talk to.

00:11:26.100 --> 00:11:28.210
All right, why don't we
go ahead and reconvene.

00:11:28.210 --> 00:11:30.606
I know that there was quite
a lot of disagreement,

00:11:30.606 --> 00:11:32.480
so that means that you
guys will probably not

00:11:32.480 --> 00:11:35.280
be able to converge in
this one minute time frame.

00:11:35.280 --> 00:11:39.160
But let me just see, let
me see if anybody's mind

00:11:39.160 --> 00:11:40.550
was changed by their neighbors.

00:11:40.550 --> 00:11:42.190
All right, let's re-vote.

00:11:42.190 --> 00:11:45.730
Ready, three, two, one.

00:11:45.730 --> 00:11:50.330
OK, all right, so
it's pretty much

00:11:50.330 --> 00:11:53.270
the same as where
we started, maybe.

00:11:53.270 --> 00:11:54.970
All right.

00:11:54.970 --> 00:11:57.610
OK I would say-- does
anybody want to volunteer

00:11:57.610 --> 00:11:59.747
what their neighbor said?

00:11:59.747 --> 00:12:01.080
I know what your neighbors said.

00:12:01.080 --> 00:12:03.550
So tell us.

00:12:03.550 --> 00:12:07.130
AUDIENCE: OK, so if you--
so I would say it's E.

00:12:07.130 --> 00:12:09.130
And the reason is that--
so there are two cases.

00:12:09.130 --> 00:12:12.260
In the first case, both the
number A and B stay the same.

00:12:12.260 --> 00:12:15.050
Right, for example, A
gets born and A dies.

00:12:15.050 --> 00:12:18.226
So you first decide, is the
pop-- is the number of A and B

00:12:18.226 --> 00:12:20.499
going to change, or is
it not going to change?

00:12:20.499 --> 00:12:21.082
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:12:21.082 --> 00:12:22.873
AUDIENCE: Once you've
decided that it's not

00:12:22.873 --> 00:12:24.550
going to change-- I'm sorry.

00:12:24.550 --> 00:12:25.750
Once you've decided that
it is going to change--

00:12:25.750 --> 00:12:26.690
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:12:26.690 --> 00:12:28.481
AUDIENCE: --then you
just want to know, OK,

00:12:28.481 --> 00:12:31.762
then what's the probability
that you just choose A to change

00:12:31.762 --> 00:12:33.590
[INAUDIBLE].

00:12:33.590 --> 00:12:35.051
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:12:35.051 --> 00:12:35.550
Yeah.

00:12:35.550 --> 00:12:37.542
AUDIENCE: And then the
probability that A--

00:12:37.542 --> 00:12:38.540
you choose--

00:12:38.540 --> 00:12:39.520
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:12:39.520 --> 00:12:42.590
But you haven't said anything
about replacement yet.

00:12:42.590 --> 00:12:46.830
So I'm-- replacement should
be-- because certainly,

00:12:46.830 --> 00:12:49.620
we're talking about the ratio of
the probability that the number

00:12:49.620 --> 00:12:52.120
of A goes up, as compared to
the probability that the number

00:12:52.120 --> 00:12:52.810
of A goes down.

00:12:52.810 --> 00:12:53.310
Right?

00:12:53.310 --> 00:12:56.160
So we've already, in some
ways, excluded the cases

00:12:56.160 --> 00:12:59.540
where the number of A
individuals doesn't change.

00:12:59.540 --> 00:13:02.300
And in your-- what
you just told us,

00:13:02.300 --> 00:13:03.790
you're asking about
the probability

00:13:03.790 --> 00:13:08.831
that individuals are going
to be chosen to reproduce.

00:13:08.831 --> 00:13:11.657
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
because [INAUDIBLE].

00:13:11.657 --> 00:13:12.240
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:13:12.240 --> 00:13:13.465
Yeah, but I guess
all I'm saying is

00:13:13.465 --> 00:13:14.850
that there're going to be
two halves to this, right?

00:13:14.850 --> 00:13:15.990
So you have to think
about the probability

00:13:15.990 --> 00:13:18.910
that an individual is being
chosen to reproduce, and also

00:13:18.910 --> 00:13:22.440
the probability that a
particular type of individual

00:13:22.440 --> 00:13:24.260
will be chosen to get replaced.

00:13:24.260 --> 00:13:26.660
So it's the-- there's somehow
a balance of those two.

00:13:26.660 --> 00:13:28.004
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:28.004 --> 00:13:29.670
PROFESSOR: Right,
because in this case--

00:13:29.670 --> 00:13:30.180
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] replace--

00:13:30.180 --> 00:13:33.340
PROFESSOR: --replace, this is--
right, death, slash-- right.

00:13:33.340 --> 00:13:35.680
And I should maybe just
highlight-- if you want,

00:13:35.680 --> 00:13:37.490
you could call--
replacement-- I mean,

00:13:37.490 --> 00:13:40.566
this is just a nice way
of saying death, right?

00:13:40.566 --> 00:13:41.065
Death--

00:13:44.641 --> 00:13:45.640
AUDIENCE: Yeah, you can.

00:13:45.640 --> 00:13:48.150
I mean, [? the point ?]
[? is ?] once you've ruled out--

00:13:48.150 --> 00:13:49.941
once you say, OK, the
populations are going

00:13:49.941 --> 00:13:53.940
to change, then if you choose an
A to reproduce, a B has to die.

00:13:53.940 --> 00:13:55.836
PROFESSOR: Oh, OK,
once you've already--

00:13:55.836 --> 00:13:57.544
AUDIENCE: If an A is
chosen to reproduce,

00:13:57.544 --> 00:13:59.040
and an A is chosen
to die, then--

00:13:59.040 --> 00:14:00.489
PROFESSOR: OK, yeah, right.

00:14:00.489 --> 00:14:02.530
But, OK, I think I understand
what you're saying.

00:14:02.530 --> 00:14:05.000
But we-- you still have
to keep track of there

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:06.060
are the two sides.

00:14:06.060 --> 00:14:07.810
There's the replace--
there's the birth,

00:14:07.810 --> 00:14:08.685
and the replacements.

00:14:08.685 --> 00:14:12.180
And we have to figure out how
the relative probabilities

00:14:12.180 --> 00:14:14.144
or rates that those
two things happen.

00:14:14.144 --> 00:14:16.560
Does somebody want to make an
argument for something else?

00:14:16.560 --> 00:14:18.737
I mean, we'll see how this
plays out in a moment.

00:14:18.737 --> 00:14:20.078
AUDIENCE: I want to argue for C.

00:14:20.078 --> 00:14:21.420
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:14:21.420 --> 00:14:22.859
AUDIENCE: So take the numerator.

00:14:22.859 --> 00:14:23.525
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:14:23.525 --> 00:14:26.000
AUDIENCE: In order to
go from i to i plus 1--

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:27.857
so we're going to
take two individuals

00:14:27.857 --> 00:14:28.690
from the population.

00:14:28.690 --> 00:14:31.695
We need one of them to be
type A, that's the one that's

00:14:31.695 --> 00:14:32.514
going to reproduce.

00:14:32.514 --> 00:14:33.005
PROFESSOR: Yep.

00:14:33.005 --> 00:14:34.478
AUDIENCE: And the other to
be type B, the one that's

