00:59:38.130 --> 00:59:47.820
i, which is the
probability that A fixes,

00:59:47.820 --> 00:59:49.685
is equal to this expression.

00:59:58.980 --> 01:00:06.310
If A fixes, given
i A individuals

01:00:06.310 --> 01:00:08.870
and N minus i B individuals.

01:00:08.870 --> 01:00:11.153
AUDIENCE: So I guess that
this assumes that they die

01:00:11.153 --> 01:00:12.850
at the same rate [INAUDIBLE].

01:00:12.850 --> 01:00:13.850
PROFESSOR: That's right.

01:00:13.850 --> 01:00:14.391
That's right.

01:00:14.391 --> 01:00:17.410
The assumption is that we're
placement is unbiased, purely

01:00:17.410 --> 01:00:24.650
random, and it's only birth that
is different by a factor of r.

01:00:24.650 --> 01:00:28.710
And so I think that this
is, on one level, wonderful.

01:00:28.710 --> 01:00:32.410
It's kind of a simple
expression describing

01:00:32.410 --> 01:00:35.010
a lot of information
of the dynamics

01:00:35.010 --> 01:00:36.180
of the stochastic process.

01:00:38.552 --> 01:00:40.760
On another level, the problem
is that you look at it,

01:00:40.760 --> 01:00:44.560
and I think it's easy to have
like absolutely zero intuition

01:00:44.560 --> 01:00:47.090
for what this thing does.

01:00:47.090 --> 01:00:52.110
So what I always like to do when
a student comes to my office

01:00:52.110 --> 01:00:55.740
and says, oh I derived
something great for our project.

01:00:55.740 --> 01:00:58.860
You take a few
limits to get a sense

01:00:58.860 --> 01:01:00.550
of what's going on with it.

01:01:00.550 --> 01:01:02.360
At half-time you find
that it's not true.

01:01:02.360 --> 01:01:05.650
But at least it's a way
of developing intuition

01:01:05.650 --> 01:01:07.210
for what's happening.

01:01:07.210 --> 01:01:10.970
All right, so what are limits
that this thing should behave--

01:01:13.946 --> 01:01:19.450
AUDIENCE: It should
be 0 if there's no A.

01:01:19.450 --> 01:01:25.510
PROFESSOR: Right, so x of
0 should be equal to 0,

01:01:25.510 --> 01:01:27.260
is what you're saying.

01:01:27.260 --> 01:01:28.970
If you have 0
individuals, you should

01:01:28.970 --> 01:01:31.911
have 0 probability of fixing,
independent of your fitness,

01:01:31.911 --> 01:01:32.410
right?

01:01:35.780 --> 01:01:39.240
All right, that sounds like
a reasonable thing to check.

01:01:39.240 --> 01:01:42.160
And does it work?

01:01:42.160 --> 01:01:44.590
So r to the 0 is equal to 1.

01:01:44.590 --> 01:01:47.750
So that's 1, so
it's 1 minus 1-- 0.

01:01:47.750 --> 01:01:50.565
Yep.

01:01:50.565 --> 01:01:51.555
Yes?

01:01:51.555 --> 01:01:54.030
AUDIENCE: r goes to
infinity independently

01:01:54.030 --> 01:01:58.561
of what you start with in step
zero, then you expect A to fix?

01:01:58.561 --> 01:01:59.560
PROFESSOR: That's right.

01:01:59.560 --> 01:02:06.090
So the limit of xi for
any i other than 0--

01:02:06.090 --> 01:02:10.580
as r goes to infinity,
this should be equal to 1.

01:02:16.240 --> 01:02:18.400
All right, so let's see.

01:02:18.400 --> 01:02:29.526
If r goes to infinity, you get
0-- this is also 0-- 1 divided

01:02:29.526 --> 01:02:31.320
by 1 is equal to 1-- all right.

01:02:34.120 --> 01:02:35.370
Did everybody agree with that?

01:02:39.410 --> 01:02:44.109
And that makes sense just that
if A is just super, super fit,

01:02:44.109 --> 01:02:44.900
then it should fix.

01:02:47.590 --> 01:02:49.010
And of course,
what's tricky here

01:02:49.010 --> 01:02:53.380
is that r has to be surprisingly
large before this thing ends up

01:02:53.380 --> 01:02:56.170
being true.

01:02:56.170 --> 01:03:00.370
This limit is great, and
it's correct and true,

01:03:00.370 --> 01:03:01.870
but it's also a
little bit dangerous

01:03:01.870 --> 01:03:06.810
because-- well we'll see
that even things that you

01:03:06.810 --> 01:03:10.390
think of as being very
beneficial mutations typically

01:03:10.390 --> 01:03:11.310
do not fix.

01:03:11.310 --> 01:03:17.690
So this is the danger, but at
least the limit is still true.

01:03:17.690 --> 01:03:20.560
Any other limits that we
think ought to happen?

01:03:20.560 --> 01:03:23.537
AUDIENCE: If an i goes to N?

01:03:23.537 --> 01:03:24.620
PROFESSOR: An i goes to N?

01:03:24.620 --> 01:03:27.040
OK, right.

01:03:27.040 --> 01:03:28.560
This is the opposite
of this one.

01:03:28.560 --> 01:03:32.266
This is just saying that if
you already have fixed then

01:03:32.266 --> 01:03:32.765
you fixed.

01:03:36.270 --> 01:03:38.425
Indeed, if i is equal
to N-- that works.

01:03:42.970 --> 01:03:47.046
Any other limits that you
believe should be true,

01:03:47.046 --> 01:03:47.920
think should be true?

01:03:47.920 --> 01:03:52.200
AUDIENCE: The one we already
checked for r equals one?

01:03:52.200 --> 01:03:53.591
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:03:53.591 --> 01:03:54.090
Indeed.

01:03:54.090 --> 01:04:00.860
So if it's neutral-- so the
limit as r goes to 1 of xi

01:04:00.860 --> 01:04:03.104
should be equal to what?

01:04:03.104 --> 01:04:04.030
AUDIENCE: i/N.

01:04:04.030 --> 01:04:06.730
PROFESSOR: Should be
equal to i/N. So this one

01:04:06.730 --> 01:04:10.570
is a little bit less
obvious, because if you

01:04:10.570 --> 01:04:20.537
set r equal to 1, does this
mean that it's equal to 0?

01:04:20.537 --> 01:04:21.495
And what's the problem?

01:04:24.360 --> 01:04:25.193
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:04:28.620 --> 01:04:31.710
PROFESSOR: Well, OK, but even
that statement's not true.

01:04:31.710 --> 01:04:33.985
It's not even
necessarily close to 0.

01:04:33.985 --> 01:04:35.360
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
L'Hopitals?

01:04:35.360 --> 01:04:36.068
PROFESSOR: Right.

01:04:36.068 --> 01:04:37.746
This is the L'Hopitals.

01:04:37.746 --> 01:04:39.120
There was another
context already

01:04:39.120 --> 01:04:41.360
were L'Hopitals came up, right?

01:04:41.360 --> 01:04:42.810
Maybe?

01:04:42.810 --> 01:04:45.440
OK, so the problem is that
if you set r equal to 1 here,

01:04:45.440 --> 01:04:46.140
then you get 0.

01:04:46.140 --> 01:04:48.220
So then you think,
oh, the answer is 0.

01:04:48.220 --> 01:04:50.720
But you have to be more careful
than that, because this also

01:04:50.720 --> 01:04:53.710
is equal to 0.

01:04:53.710 --> 01:05:03.010
And so L'Hopital's-- L-H-
-- is it above the H?

01:05:07.510 --> 01:05:08.820
AUDIENCE: No, that looks right.

01:05:08.820 --> 01:05:09.360
PROFESSOR: Is it good?

01:05:09.360 --> 01:05:09.943
AUDIENCE: Yes.

01:05:09.943 --> 01:05:11.420
PROFESSOR: All right.

01:05:11.420 --> 01:05:12.960
You're French, right?

01:05:12.960 --> 01:05:14.680
I mean, sort of.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:22.755
He's from Quebec, so I don't
know what that question--

01:05:22.755 --> 01:05:23.630
how it's interpreted.

01:05:26.740 --> 01:05:28.500
So this [INAUDIBLE]
looks all right.

01:05:28.500 --> 01:05:31.450
See, what you just
have to do is then

01:05:31.450 --> 01:05:33.600
you take the
derivative with respect

01:05:33.600 --> 01:05:36.240
to r for both the numerator
and the denominator,

01:05:36.240 --> 01:05:38.940
and then you see what ha--
but you take the limit again.

01:05:38.940 --> 01:05:41.130
And sometimes you have
to apply L'Hopital's rule

01:05:41.130 --> 01:05:42.610
multiple times, right?

01:05:42.610 --> 01:05:47.630
So what we write here is this
is the limit as r goes to 1,

01:05:47.630 --> 01:05:51.810
and we take the derivative of
the numerator respect to r.

01:05:51.810 --> 01:06:00.540
So we get out an i, 1 over
r to the i plus 1, maybe?

01:06:06.470 --> 01:06:14.960
And here we get out an N.

01:06:14.960 --> 01:06:18.940
All right, so we took the
derivatives back to r here.

01:06:18.940 --> 01:06:20.750
But we left it as a
limit because we might

01:06:20.750 --> 01:06:22.170
need to apply it again, right?

01:06:22.170 --> 01:06:23.440
Just because after you
take the derivative

01:06:23.440 --> 01:06:25.731
you're not guaranteed that
it's going to work out fine,

01:06:25.731 --> 01:06:26.800
but in this case it does.

01:06:26.800 --> 01:06:28.850
Because already,
this limit, we're

01:06:28.850 --> 01:06:32.320
allowed to just set equal to
1 because nothing blows up.

01:06:32.320 --> 01:06:38.270
So this is indeed
equal to i/N. N.

01:06:38.270 --> 01:06:41.250
And the important point here
is that it's not necessarily

01:06:41.250 --> 01:06:43.080
approximately equal to 0.

01:06:43.080 --> 01:06:46.690
It could be anywhere
between 0 and 1

01:06:46.690 --> 01:06:49.490
depending what i and N are.

01:06:49.490 --> 01:06:52.150
PROFESSOR: So that means
that this expression here

01:06:52.150 --> 01:06:58.142
captures the dynamics,
actually, for all i, r,

01:06:58.142 --> 01:07:01.630
N within the Moran process.

01:07:01.630 --> 01:07:07.320
This thing is simply
just true in this model.

01:07:07.320 --> 01:07:11.020
There are no approximations yet.

01:07:11.020 --> 01:07:13.205
There is, however,
one approximation

01:07:13.205 --> 01:07:16.300
that is very useful
to make, which

01:07:16.300 --> 01:07:19.170
is the approximation
of what happens

01:07:19.170 --> 01:07:22.130
when r is approximately 1.

01:07:27.949 --> 01:07:29.490
In particular what
we're going to ask

01:07:29.490 --> 01:07:32.450
is, if we define something
called a selection

01:07:32.450 --> 01:07:46.020
coefficient, that is
1 plus s, the idea

01:07:46.020 --> 01:07:49.664
here is that in many
cases-- well for Thursday

01:07:49.664 --> 01:07:51.330
we're going to read
a paper that I think

01:07:51.330 --> 01:07:53.000
this is quite interesting.

01:07:53.000 --> 01:07:59.080
And where they were
analyzing the appearance

01:07:59.080 --> 01:08:01.180
of these mutations
that would allow

01:08:01.180 --> 01:08:04.790
bacteria to survive in some
environment to do better.

01:08:04.790 --> 01:08:06.310
And typical selection
coefficients

01:08:06.310 --> 01:08:09.990
here are kind of 1% to 3%.

01:08:09.990 --> 01:08:13.980
So the mutations that appear and
that allow one of these cells

01:08:13.980 --> 01:08:15.610
to do better in this
new environment,

01:08:15.610 --> 01:08:20.240
convert an advantage that was
on the order of 1% or 2%, or so.

01:08:20.240 --> 01:08:24.580
Which means that s here
would be like 0.01, 0.02.

01:08:24.580 --> 01:08:28.040
Which means that for basically
all the situations that you

01:08:28.040 --> 01:08:30.529
see in the laboratory and
so forth, what you really

01:08:30.529 --> 01:08:34.390
want to know is what
happens for small s.

01:08:34.390 --> 01:08:36.770
So for s, much less than 1.

01:08:36.770 --> 01:08:38.713
So where r is
approximately equal to 1.

01:08:45.029 --> 01:08:51.750
And in this case, we
can say xi, well--

01:08:51.750 --> 01:08:56.670
and we actually are going to
want to ask about x sub 1.

01:08:56.670 --> 01:08:58.370
So that's a 1 now.

01:09:02.010 --> 01:09:04.010
And the reason for that
is that we want to know,

01:09:04.010 --> 01:09:06.370
are there some rate
that new mutations

01:09:06.370 --> 01:09:07.632
will appear in the population?

01:09:07.632 --> 01:09:10.090
When they appear they'll be
present in a single individual,

01:09:10.090 --> 01:09:13.130
and we want to know what
is the probability that one

01:09:13.130 --> 01:09:17.460
individual-- let's say
has a beneficial mutation,

01:09:17.460 --> 01:09:21.410
well, the probability it'll
fix-- so we want to know

01:09:21.410 --> 01:09:27.500
is for s, much less than
1, but larger than 0.

01:09:27.500 --> 01:09:30.720
So far, it's a beneficial
mutation of modest effect.

01:09:30.720 --> 01:09:33.580
What's the probability
that it will fix?

01:09:33.580 --> 01:09:40.359
Well the idea here
is that r to the N

01:09:40.359 --> 01:09:44.590
is going to be much larger
than 1, because N is often

01:09:44.590 --> 01:09:47.460
a big population.

01:09:47.460 --> 01:09:50.040
Now in that situation,
this is just

01:09:50.040 --> 01:09:53.490
approximately equal to 1 over r.

01:09:58.350 --> 01:10:01.920
And r, we've already decided
it can be expressed as 1

01:10:01.920 --> 01:10:05.390
plus the selection coefficient.

01:10:05.390 --> 01:10:08.490
Now this is something
that you want

01:10:08.490 --> 01:10:14.270
to be able to simplify
in your sleep.

01:10:14.270 --> 01:10:16.630
1 divided by 1 plus
s is approximately

01:10:16.630 --> 01:10:19.560
equal to 1 minus 1 minus s.

01:10:24.790 --> 01:10:27.190
And this is indeed
approximately equal to s.

01:10:30.580 --> 01:10:33.600
This is saying that
in the Moran process,

01:10:33.600 --> 01:10:36.180
if a beneficial mutation
appears in the population

01:10:36.180 --> 01:10:41.230
with selection code coefficient
s, that might be 1% to 3%,

01:10:41.230 --> 01:10:46.040
then it has a 1% to 3%
probability of surviving.

01:10:46.040 --> 01:10:49.180
Because this is the
probability of fixing,

01:10:49.180 --> 01:10:51.627
but in this situation
fixation and survival

01:10:51.627 --> 01:10:53.210
are the same thing,
because we're just

01:10:53.210 --> 01:10:55.730
considering this one mutation.

01:10:55.730 --> 01:10:57.120
So it's the only
thing that we're

01:10:57.120 --> 01:10:59.480
considering is the fate of this
one mutation of the population.

01:10:59.480 --> 01:11:00.870
We're going to assume
for now that you

01:11:00.870 --> 01:11:03.286
can't get new mutations in the
population to compete with.

01:11:03.286 --> 01:11:05.040
And then either you
go extinct, or you

01:11:05.040 --> 01:11:07.610
take over the population.

01:11:07.610 --> 01:11:11.120
And what's surprising
here is that even

01:11:11.120 --> 01:11:16.290
if it's a fact that you think
it was big, like 3%, 4%.

01:11:16.290 --> 01:11:18.380
I would love to get
such a mutation.

01:11:18.380 --> 01:11:22.420
But still, in a population
in the Moran process,

01:11:22.420 --> 01:11:25.350
or really in any
other model like this,

01:11:25.350 --> 01:11:28.900
it will typically go extinct.

01:11:28.900 --> 01:11:31.990
Now, it's worth
saying that depending

01:11:31.990 --> 01:11:35.290
upon the model
that you're using,

01:11:35.290 --> 01:11:40.050
you'll get different
numbers in here.

01:11:40.050 --> 01:11:43.900
In this case, the probability
of fixation or survival

01:11:43.900 --> 01:11:46.000
is 1 times s.

01:11:46.000 --> 01:11:47.650
But in some other
models and it depends

01:11:47.650 --> 01:11:48.720
on the branching process.

01:11:48.720 --> 01:11:50.460
It could be two times s.

01:11:50.460 --> 01:11:55.185
But it's something of
order unity times s.

01:11:55.185 --> 01:12:03.610
AUDIENCE: And so we say that
if s is equal to 0, then x of 1

01:12:03.610 --> 01:12:05.570
should be--

01:12:05.570 --> 01:12:06.460
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:12:06.460 --> 01:12:08.640
PROFESSOR: Right.

01:12:08.640 --> 01:12:09.140
Exactly.

01:12:09.140 --> 01:12:10.973
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
assume that s is much,

01:12:10.973 --> 01:12:12.819
much greater than 1/N?

01:12:12.819 --> 01:12:13.610
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

01:12:13.610 --> 01:12:19.030
So what we've assumed
is that this is true

01:12:19.030 --> 01:12:25.870
and that I think that's
actually already sufficient.

01:12:25.870 --> 01:12:30.960
And indeed, you can go and
you can do the expansion

01:12:30.960 --> 01:12:35.030
and find what x sub 1 should
be equal to in general here.

01:12:35.030 --> 01:12:41.420
And for small s, but
including the possibility

01:12:41.420 --> 01:12:45.935
that it's very-- I'm sorry-- for
small s but not super small s.

01:12:45.935 --> 01:12:47.685
It's a matter of what
you're comparing to.

01:12:50.540 --> 01:12:55.310
And you end up
getting 1/N plus s/2.

01:12:58.380 --> 01:13:04.780
And this is for s times
N much less than 1.

01:13:09.010 --> 01:13:10.980
And indeed, this
is the definition

01:13:10.980 --> 01:13:13.170
of what we mean
by nearly neutral.

01:13:18.580 --> 01:13:21.530
Because up to now we've been
talking about neutral mutations

01:13:21.530 --> 01:13:24.570
as if they just had to be
exactly, exactly neutral,

01:13:24.570 --> 01:13:29.220
but then really, that probably
doesn't actually literally

01:13:29.220 --> 01:13:29.990
exist.

01:13:29.990 --> 01:13:32.790
But if a mutation appears and
it only changes your fitness

01:13:32.790 --> 01:13:35.790
by one part in 10
to the minus 30,

01:13:35.790 --> 01:13:40.220
then it is equivalent to being
a truly neutral mutation.

01:13:40.220 --> 01:13:43.060
But the way that you
quantify that is this thing.

01:13:43.060 --> 01:13:45.270
s times N. You want
to know whether it's

01:13:45.270 --> 01:13:46.760
larger or smaller than 1.

01:13:51.300 --> 01:14:00.285
So for example if you plot x
sub 1 as a function of s-- 0,

01:14:00.285 --> 01:14:02.590
right?

01:14:02.590 --> 01:14:04.326
It crosses 1 over N here.

01:14:08.520 --> 01:14:14.070
Now, it's going to have
a slope here-- s over 2--

01:14:14.070 --> 01:14:16.220
but then it kind of goes up.

01:14:16.220 --> 01:14:22.075
It eventually hits this--
this is just the s line--

01:14:22.075 --> 01:14:25.410
because if s is
much less than 1,

01:14:25.410 --> 01:14:29.590
yet s times N is
much larger than 1,

01:14:29.590 --> 01:14:31.635
then x1 is approximately
equal to s.

01:14:34.240 --> 01:14:38.925
And then over here, this
goes down exponentially.

01:14:43.080 --> 01:14:46.190
But the statement is that if
s times N is much less than 1,

01:14:46.190 --> 01:14:50.590
then the mutation acts
essentially as if it's neutral.

01:14:50.590 --> 01:14:53.830
So then you can
just work with that,

01:14:53.830 --> 01:14:56.160
whereas, if s times N
is much larger than 1,

01:14:56.160 --> 01:14:58.700
then you end up--
it's not guaranteed

01:14:58.700 --> 01:15:02.200
that it's going to fix, but it's
much larger than a probability

01:15:02.200 --> 01:15:06.120
of 1/N. Whereas down
here, it becomes

01:15:06.120 --> 01:15:10.434
very unlikely to fix once
s times N is larger than 1

01:15:10.434 --> 01:15:11.392
on the deleterial side.

01:15:17.300 --> 01:15:20.320
Are there any questions
about what's going on here?

01:15:20.320 --> 01:15:20.820
Yes.

01:15:20.820 --> 01:15:23.814
AUDIENCE: I'm wondering
about that factor of 1/2.

01:15:23.814 --> 01:15:29.053
[INAUDIBLE] seems like we didn't
get it over here when we had N

01:15:29.053 --> 01:15:30.121
equals--

01:15:30.121 --> 01:15:31.120
PROFESSOR: That's right.

01:15:31.120 --> 01:15:31.855
Yeah, sorry.

01:15:31.855 --> 01:15:33.980
And indeed, when I did this
calculation originally,

01:15:33.980 --> 01:15:36.354
I was very confused, because
I thought it should be that.

01:15:36.354 --> 01:15:38.330
But what you see is
that if you plot this,

01:15:38.330 --> 01:15:42.501
the slope here, which is
the 1/2, is less than slope

01:15:42.501 --> 01:15:43.417
over here, which is 1.

01:15:51.369 --> 01:15:52.363
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:15:57.656 --> 01:15:59.780
PROFESSOR: Well, what's
funny is, I actually spent,

01:15:59.780 --> 01:16:01.400
like, hours, trying
to figure out

01:16:01.400 --> 01:16:03.830
where I had made my mistakes.

01:16:03.830 --> 01:16:06.880
No, but I think that
if you just draw it,

01:16:06.880 --> 01:16:08.635
I think it's all consistent.

01:16:08.635 --> 01:16:09.510
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:16:12.870 --> 01:16:15.660
PROFESSOR: I mean, I'm
plotting the entire curve,

01:16:15.660 --> 01:16:17.656
analytically, perfectly.

01:16:17.656 --> 01:16:19.510
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:16:19.510 --> 01:16:23.520
PROFESSOR: It's just
that what we know,

01:16:23.520 --> 01:16:25.600
is that it behaves
like this around here,

01:16:25.600 --> 01:16:33.409
and like s up here, and
I've just connected them--

01:16:33.409 --> 01:16:35.450
it probably doesn't answer
your question but it--

01:16:39.900 --> 01:16:42.610
So I think we have just
enough time to say something

01:16:42.610 --> 01:16:44.090
about this Muller's
ratchet idea.

01:16:46.660 --> 01:16:50.820
Verbally, can a deleterious
mutation, s less than 0,

01:16:50.820 --> 01:16:52.450
can it fix in a population?

01:16:52.450 --> 01:16:52.950
Yes or no?

01:16:52.950 --> 01:16:55.487
Ready, three, two, one.

01:16:55.487 --> 01:16:56.070
AUDIENCE: Yes.

01:16:56.070 --> 01:16:58.500
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:16:58.500 --> 01:17:00.650
This is greater than 0.

01:17:00.650 --> 01:17:04.070
Now it's, very unlikely to
fix if the negative s times N

01:17:04.070 --> 01:17:06.040
is much larger than 1.

01:17:06.040 --> 01:17:10.040
But for small size
populations, you

01:17:10.040 --> 01:17:13.140
could actually fix relatively
deleterious mutations.

01:17:15.840 --> 01:17:20.090
So the idea is that
for small populations,

01:17:20.090 --> 01:17:23.330
it's easy to accumulate
deleterious mutations.

01:17:23.330 --> 01:17:26.738
And indeed, This is related
to something called a mutation

01:17:26.738 --> 01:17:27.529
accumulation assay.

01:17:33.120 --> 01:17:35.230
So if you take a
population of bacteria

01:17:35.230 --> 01:17:47.500
or other microorganism--
so you grow up

01:17:47.500 --> 01:17:49.780
your bacteria in a test tube.

01:17:49.780 --> 01:17:51.990
And so you have a
bunch of bacteria.

01:17:51.990 --> 01:17:54.490
So now there's selection acting
in here, because the faster

01:17:54.490 --> 01:17:56.040
dividing cells are spreading.

01:17:56.040 --> 01:18:00.790
However, what you do is that
you then plate them as colonies.

01:18:00.790 --> 01:18:03.976
And these colonies each
started as single cells.

01:18:03.976 --> 01:18:05.350
Then what you do
is you just take

01:18:05.350 --> 01:18:10.760
a random cell, a random colony,
that came from a single cell,

01:18:10.760 --> 01:18:14.920
and you grow it up here.

01:18:14.920 --> 01:18:17.572
Or you could just replay
directly if you like.

01:18:17.572 --> 01:18:19.155
And then you just
repeat this process.

01:18:22.040 --> 01:18:27.744
The idea is that you've
picked a random cell

01:18:27.744 --> 01:18:29.910
from this population that
you allowed it to grow up,

01:18:29.910 --> 01:18:32.160
and so you've kind of removed
the effects of selection

01:18:32.160 --> 01:18:34.220
in here.

01:18:34.220 --> 01:18:35.910
So when you pick a
random colony here,

01:18:35.910 --> 01:18:37.706
maybe that colony got
some weird mutation

01:18:37.706 --> 01:18:40.080
that decreased its fitness,
but it wasn't really selected

01:18:40.080 --> 01:18:41.810
against because you
just kind of picked

01:18:41.810 --> 01:18:44.440
one of these colonies randomly.

01:18:44.440 --> 01:18:47.610
So this kind of process
is a way of reducing

01:18:47.610 --> 01:18:50.155
what's known as the effective
population size-- N effective.

01:18:52.730 --> 01:18:56.020
So when populations are
not constant in time,

01:18:56.020 --> 01:18:58.420
but instead oscillate
or fluctuate,

01:18:58.420 --> 01:19:03.040
then in many cases the dynamics
or the strength of this drift,

01:19:03.040 --> 01:19:05.900
or the stochastic stuff,
that could be characterized

01:19:05.900 --> 01:19:06.755
by some ineffective.

01:19:06.755 --> 01:19:09.170
And of course, depending
on which variable

01:19:09.170 --> 01:19:11.171
or which quantity
you're trying to study,

01:19:11.171 --> 01:19:13.170
you might have a slightly
different N effective.

01:19:13.170 --> 01:19:15.930
But the point is that if you
have fluctuating population

01:19:15.930 --> 01:19:21.420
sizes, then the relevant
population size for thinking

01:19:21.420 --> 01:19:23.650
about these sorts
of ideas, is often

01:19:23.650 --> 01:19:25.590
towards the smaller
side of the range

01:19:25.590 --> 01:19:26.840
of the fluctuating population.

01:19:26.840 --> 01:19:31.284
So you're kind of dominated by
how small the bottleneck gets.

01:19:31.284 --> 01:19:33.450
And here, you're kind of
going through a single cell

01:19:33.450 --> 01:19:36.190
bottleneck, so that leads
to a very small N effective,

01:19:36.190 --> 01:19:38.039
and it allows for
the accumulation

01:19:38.039 --> 01:19:39.080
of deleterious mutations.

01:19:44.905 --> 01:19:47.280
Now, we'll say something more
about this Muller's ratchet

01:19:47.280 --> 01:19:50.080
idea, because in the
field of evolution,

01:19:50.080 --> 01:19:53.340
I'd say one of the big
overriding questions

01:19:53.340 --> 01:19:56.590
is trying to understand
the evolutionary advantages

01:19:56.590 --> 01:19:59.030
of sexual reproduction.

01:19:59.030 --> 01:20:02.220
Because of this famous
twofold cost of sex.

01:20:02.220 --> 01:20:04.760
That it seems that
an asexual population

01:20:04.760 --> 01:20:08.830
should be able to grow
twice as fast as a sexually

01:20:08.830 --> 01:20:13.440
reproducing population, because
the males are not giving birth.

01:20:13.440 --> 01:20:15.940
So it's a huge cost associated
with sexual reproduction.

01:20:15.940 --> 01:20:20.020
The question is, why is it that
so many organisms engage in it?

01:20:20.020 --> 01:20:23.800
And one of the explanations
that's been proposed

01:20:23.800 --> 01:20:26.680
is this Muller's
ratchet idea, that it

01:20:26.680 --> 01:20:31.320
may alleviate this accumulation
of deleterious mutations.

01:20:31.320 --> 01:20:34.270
We'll talk more about
how this works out,

01:20:34.270 --> 01:20:36.630
maybe quantitatively,
and the other proposals

01:20:36.630 --> 01:20:39.710
and so forth later, but
you may, over the course

01:20:39.710 --> 01:20:42.350
of your studies, come across
this Muller's ratchet vis-a-vis

01:20:42.350 --> 01:20:43.850
the question of
sexual reproduction.

01:20:43.850 --> 01:20:45.475
So I just wanted you
to know that there

01:20:45.475 --> 01:20:48.200
is this discussion out there,
about how sexual reproduction

01:20:48.200 --> 01:20:51.270
may allow for the separation
of these beneficial and

01:20:51.270 --> 01:20:54.000
deleterious mutations
that would otherwise

01:20:54.000 --> 01:20:56.150
accumulate in the population.

